Tuberculoid to lepromatous is a spectrum. Lepromatous is the severe form.
Tuberculoid

  • Few hypopigmented patches only and some nerve involvement.
  • Tuberculoid form is not infectious.

Immune suppressed persons will get lepromatous leprosy.

  • Multibacillary - 12 months (rifampicin 600 monthly, clofaziime 300 monthly, dapsone daily. )
  • Paucibacillary - 6 months (Rifampicin 600, dapsone ?daily)

MDT treatment should not be stopped for 'lepra' reactions (see below)

  • type 1 reactions : existing lesions become red and nerve reactions
    These are not drug reactions; treatment is continued. (unless a drug reaction occurs)

Even skin biopsy is not needed if clinically very suggestive of leprosy.
📑
In BL and LL leprosy, sensation and hair are preserved in the lesions!
There are type 1 and 2 lepra reactions.
Can even occur years after treatment is completed.

Both share symptoms of neuritis, arthritis, iritis and nasopharyngeal symptoms.
Can lead to severe nerve injury with subsequence paralysis and deformity.

  • Usually occurs in borderline disease (BT-BL)

  • Induration, swelling or erythema of previous lesions.

  • appears to result from spontaneous enhancement of cellular immunity and delayed-type hypersensitivity to M. leprae antigens

  • May rupture and discharge pus but they contain only dead bacteria and neutrophils -> sterile on culture.

  • Biopsy of lesions will show polymorph -> diagnostic of type 2 reactions. (polymorphs not present in other lepromatous lesions).

  • Occurs in Lepromatous or Borderline lepromatous disease.

  • Lucio phenomenon: very rare; occurs in Mexicans. Necrotising punched punched out ulcers. Can be life threatening.
    M leprae is an obligate, intracellular parasite -> can't be cultured on normal media.
    Clofazimine causes a copper (red and dark skin and hair) pigmentation, particularly on areas exposed to light starting during the first 10 weeks of treatment. This is reversible but takes several months. Also causes icthyosis.

📑Wernicke encephalopathy
📑- Mnemonic : Altered mental state + eye signs + ataxia

  • Triad of ophthalmoplegia, ataxia, confusion, + nystagmus + lower limb polyneuropathy.
  • Is an acute condition; Reversible; requires emergency treatment to prevent death.
  • Occurs in chronic alcoholics and after bariatric surgery.
  • Other causes: severe malnutrition, hyperemesis gravidarum, prolonged parenteral nutrition (without thiamine), malignancies, immunodeficiency syndromes, liver disease, hyperthyroidism, and severe anorexia nervosa.

[!TIP] mnemonic
Beau lines - 'Bumps', 'Brake' - caused by any systemic or local insult 'putting the brakes' on nail growth.
Mees lines - caused by toxins, including arsenic
Muehrcke lines - caused by low protein

A - Mees lines, B - Baeu lines.

Beau lines and onychomadesis

  • Caused by Acute systemic illness stopping nail growth: Source
  • may be caused by infection, surgery, trauma, Raynaud disease, pemphigus or chemotherapy (i.e., taxoids).
    • They are transverse depressions of the nail.

Mees lines:

  • In Mees lines (true leukonychia) a change occurs in the colour of the nail with no palpable ridges.
  • The insult causing Mees lines does not cause cessation of nail growth. Rather there is parakeratosis of the nail bed.
  • Mees lines are associated with arsenic poisoning, Hodgkin lymphoma, carcinoid tumours and chemotherapy <- basically toxins and Hodgkin.

Muehrcke lines;

  • These are caused by vascular congestion and blanch on pressure and DO not migrate with nail growth.
    • Muehrcke lines result from liver disease, nephrotic syndrome, malnutrition and severe hypoalbuminemia

📑Sarcoidosis

Etiology unknown.
Can also involve eyes - uveitis, skin - lupus pernio.

[!INFO] Lupus pernio

Lupus pernio = cutaneous sarcoidosis
Lupus vulgaris = cutaneous tuberculosis

Heart can also be involved: Mild to life threatening spectrum.

  • Conduction: Heart block and arrhythmias
  • Muscle: Heart failure
  • Valves: Valular dysfuntion
  • simulated infarction
  • pericardial disease

Renal involvement is uncommon.

Delirium is rapid in onset and fluctuating in course.

[!INFO] Type 1 Vs. Type 2
Type 1: "more cysts, more frequent, more chromosomes"

Mutations in PKD1 gene (on chromosome 16) are responsible for 85% of cases. Rest are by PKD2 gene (on chromosome 4).

[!INFO] Autosomal recessive PCKD
Due to #autosomal-Recessive mutations carried on chromosome 6. Much rarer than ADPKD.

PKD genes encode the polycystin proteins. Mutations of these cause decreased intracellular calcium in the principal cells of the collecting duct -> dysoriented cell division -> cyst formation.

Polycystin 1 (in PKD1) is a regulator of tubular epithelial cell adhesion and differentiation. Polycystin 2 (in PKD2) is an ion channel. These are required for function of cilia of the tubular epithelium which are in turn required for flow sensing. Impaired flow sensing causes a defect in proliferation and differentiation -> cysts.

Cyst formation occurs only in 5-10% of nephrons but that's enough to cause renomegaly.

Risk factors for progressive renal disease:

  • Male gender
  • proteinuria - although it's not a major feature of PCKD.
  • High urinary sodium excretion
  • hypertension - patients with larger kidneys tend to have hypertension.
    🔴⚠️PKD1⚠️🔴 is more severe than 🟢PKD2🟢

Since the cysts grow at the same rate in both forms, it is likely that the difference is due to a higher number of cysts in type 1, rather than a higher growth rate. Source

  • proteinuria -

  • All patients with PCKD have a mild concentrating defect (one of the earliest features of the diseaes ) causing them to develop thirst, polyuria, frequency and nocturia.) - mechanism not known.

  • For patients who have a family history

    • For young adults, > total of 3 cysts
    • For older adults(40 y/o and above), > 2 cysts in each kidney.

  • For patients without a family history, there are no well defined imaging diagnostic criteria because solitary or multiple renal cysts are common, especially at age > 50%. Therefore, a cut-off of 10 or more cysts per kidney is reasonable for diagnosis of ADPKD.
    Renal cancer occurs only rarely in PCKD. It may not even be more frequent than the general population. Source

  • Cerebral vasculature aneurysms

  • Hepatic and pancreatic cysts

  • Valvular dysfunction - MR and AR + coronary aneurysms

  • Colonic diverticulae

  • Seminal vesicle cysts

  • Manage blood pressure with ACEi / ARB

  • Restrict dietary sodium

  • Higher fluid intake is recommended. (>3) -> prevents nephrolithiasis and suppresses ADH which may increase cyst growth.

  • Tolvaptan - given for high risk patients; proven benefit. (because vasopressive promotes cellular proliferation). Slows progress of disease. ?does not induce regression? #2020GM-JUL/Q29

  • Erythropoietin is actually not needed for treatment as Epo levels tend to be higher in PCKD patients. Probably stimulated secondary to local ischemia. Source

📑Serum sickness

Pathophysiology: Patient starts to produce antibodies to a non-human proteins that was introduced into the system, usually via some type of treatment. The antibodies bind the foreign protein and form antigen-antibody complexes. If they are not cleared, they deposit in tissues and the synovial fluid.

  • Monoclonal antibodies derived from animals

MDMA

(aka: ecstasy, molly)
3,4-Methyl​enedioxy​methamphetamine
party drug
Increased CNS levels of serotoning by inhibitin reuptake: Causes euphoria, alertness, 'empathogenic', but depression after the drug wears off.

They should be evaluated for hyperthermia, dehydration, hyponatremia, seizures, hypertensive crises, cardiac dysrhythmias, and possible signs of serotonin syndrome

Effects characterized by anxiety, tachycardia, and elevated blood pressures. Associated symptoms include diaphoresis, bruxism, jaw clenching, paresthesias, dry mouth, increased psychomotor activity, and blurred vision. Within 1 hour, these sympathomimetic effects are replaced by feelings of relaxation, euphoria, and increased empathy and communication.
Hallucinations are uncommon.
Toxicity: hyperthermia, serotonin syndrome,
Hyperthermia requires active cooling, antipyretics aren't useful.
(?dilutional) Hyponatremia can occur.
